Sixteen years of being addressed thus left Harry in no doubt whom his uncle was calling; nevertheless, he did not immediately respond. He was still gazing at the mirror fragment in which, for a split second, he had thought he saw Dumbledore\rquote 
s eye. It was not until his uncle bellowed \lquote BOY!\rquote  that Harry got slowly to his feet and headed for the bedroom door, pausing to add the piece of broken mirror to the rucksack filled with things he would be taking with him.
\par \lquote You took your time!\rquote  roared Vernon Dursley when Harry appeared at the top of the stairs. \lquote Get down here, I want a word!\rquote 
\par Harry strolled downstairs, his hands deep in his jeans pockets. When he reached the living ro
om, he found all three Dursleys. They were dressed for travelling: Uncle Vernon in a fawn zip-up jacket, Aunt Petunia in a neat, salmon-coloured coat and Dudley, Harry\rquote s large, blond, muscular cousin, in his leather jacket.
\par \lquote Yes?\rquote  asked Harry.
\par \lquote Sit down!\rquote  said Uncle Vernon. Harry raised his eyebrows. \lquote Please!\rquote  added Uncle Vernon, wincing slightly as though the word was sharp in his throat.
\par Harry sat. He thought he knew what was coming. His uncle began to pace up and down, Aunt Petunia and Dudley following h
is movements with anxious expressions. Finally, his large, purple face crumpled with concentration, Uncle Vernon stopped in front of Harry and spoke.
\par \lquote I\rquote ve changed my mind,\rquote  he said.
\par \lquote What a surprise,\rquote  said Harry.
\par \lquote Don\rquote t you take that tone \endash \rquote  began Aunt Petunia in a shrill voice, but Vernon Dursley waved her down.
\par \lquote It\rquote s all a lot of claptrap,\rquote  said Uncle Vernon, glaring at Harry with piggy little eyes. \lquote I\rquote ve decided I don\rquote t believe a word of it. We\rquote re staying put, we\rquote re not going anywhere.\rquote 
\par Harry looked up at his uncle and felt a mixture of exasperation and amusement. Vernon Dursley had been changing his mind every twenty-four hours for the past four weeks, packing and unpacking and repacking the car with every change of heart. Harry\rquote 
s favourite moment had been the one when Uncle Vernon, unaware that Dudley had added his dumb-bells to his case since the last time it had been unpacked, had attempted to hoist it back into the boot and collapsed with roars of pain and much swearing.

\par \lquote According to you,\rquote  Vernon Dursley said now, resuming his pacing up and down the living room, \lquote we \endash  Petunia, Dudley and I \endash  are in danger. From \endash  from \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Some of \'93my lot\'94, right,\rquote  said Harry.
\par \lquote Well, I don\rquote t believe it,\rquote  repeated Uncle Vernon, coming to a halt in front of Harry again. \lquote I was awake half the night thinking it all over, and I believe it\rquote s a plot to get the house.\rquote 
\par \lquote The house?\rquote  repeated Harry. \lquote What house?\rquote 
\par \lquote This house!\rquote  shrieked Uncle Vernon, the vein in his forehead starting to pulse. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 house! House prices are sky-rocketing round here! You want us out of the way and then you\rquote re going to do a bit of hocus-pocus and before we know it the deeds will be in your name and \endash 
\rquote 
\par \lquote Are you out of your mind?\rquote  demanded Harry. \lquote A plot to get this house? Are you actually as stupid as you look?\rquote 
\par \lquote Don\rquote t you dare \endash !\rquote  squealed Aunt Petunia, but again, Vernon waved her down: slights on his personal appearance were, it seemed, as nothing to the danger he had spotted.
\par \lquote Just in case you\rquote ve forgotten,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote I\rquote ve already got a house, my godfather left me one. So why would I want this one? All the happy memories?\rquote 
\par There was silence. Harry thought he had rather impressed his uncle with this argument.
\par \lquote You claim,\rquote  said Uncle Vernon, starting to pace yet again, \lquote that this Lord Thing \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Voldemort,\rquote  said Harry impatiently, \lquote and we\rquote ve been through this about a hundred times already. This isn\rquote t a claim, it\rquote s fact, Dumbledore told you last year, and Kingsley and Mr Weasley \endash \rquote 
\par Vernon Dursley hunched his shoulders angrily, and Harry guessed that his uncle was attempting to ward off recollections of the unannounced visit, a few days into Harry\rquote 
s summer holidays, of two fully grown wizards. The arrival on the doorstep of Kingsley Shacklebolt and Arthur Weasley had come as a most unpleasant shock t
o the Dursleys. Harry had to admit, however, that as Mr Weasley had once demolished half of the living room, his reappearance could not have been expected to delight Uncle Vernon.
\par \lquote \endash  Kingsley and Mr Weasley explained it all as well,\rquote  Harry pressed on remorselessly. \lquote Once I\rquote 
m seventeen, the protective charm that keeps me safe will break, and that exposes you as well as me. The Order is sure Voldemort will target you, whether to torture you to try and find out where I am, or because he thinks by holding you hostage I\rquote 
d come and try to rescue you.\rquote 
\par Uncle Vernon\rquote s and Harry\rquote s eyes met. Harry was sure that in that instant they were both wondering the same thing. Then Uncle Vernon walked on and Harry resumed, \lquote You\rquote ve got to go into hiding and the Order wants to help. You
\rquote re being offered serious protection, the best there is.\rquote 
\par Uncle Vernon said nothing, but continued to pace up and down. Outside, the sun hung low over the privet hedges. The next-door neighbour\rquote s lawnmower stalled again.
\par \lquote I thought there was a Ministry of Magic?\rquote  asked Vernon Dursley abruptly.
\par \lquote There is,\rquote  said Harry, surprised.
\par \lquote Well, then, why can\rquote t they protect us? It seems to me that, as innocent victims, guilty of nothing more than harbouring a marked man, we ought to qualify for government protection!\rquote 
\par Harry laughed; he could not help himself. It was so very typical of his uncle to put his hopes in the establishment, even within this world that he despised and mistrusted.
\par \lquote You heard what Mr Weasley and Kingsley said,\rquote  Harry replied. \lquote We think the Ministry has been infiltrated.\rquote 
\par Uncle Vernon strode to the fireplace and back, breathing so heavily that his great, black moustache rippled, his face still purple with concentration.
\par \lquote All right,\rquote  he said, stopping in front of Harry yet again. \lquote All right, let\rquote s say, for the sake of argument, we accept this protection. I still don\rquote t see why we can\rquote t have that Kingsley bloke.\rquote 
\par Harry managed not to roll his eyes, but with difficulty. This question had also been addressed half a dozen times.
\par \lquote As I\rquote ve told you,\rquote  he said, through gritted teeth, \lquote Kingsley is protecting the Mug\emdash  I mean, your Prime Minister.\rquote 
\par \lquote Exactly \endash  he\rquote s the best!\rquote  said Uncle Vernon, pointing at the blank television screen. The Dursleys had spotted Kingsley on the news, walking along discreetly b
ehind the Muggle Prime Minister as he visited a hospital. This, and the fact that Kingsley had mastered the knack of dressing like a Muggle, not to mention a certain reassuring something in his slow, deep voice, had caused the Dursleys to take to Kingsley
 in a way that they had certainly not done with any other wizard, although it was true that they had never seen him with his earring in.
\par \lquote Well, he\rquote s taken,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote But Hestia Jones and Dedalus Diggle are more than up to the job \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote If we\rquote d even seen CVs ...\rquote  began Uncle Vernon, but Harry lost patience. Getting to his feet, he advanced on his uncle, now pointing at the TV set himself.
\par \lquote These accidents aren\rquote t accidents \endash  the crashes and explosions and derailments and whatever else has happened since we last watched the news. People are disappearing and dying and he\rquote s behind it \endash  Voldemort. I\rquote 
ve told you this over and over again, he kills Muggles for fun. Even the fogs \endash  they\rquote re caused by Dementors, and if you can\rquote t remember what they are, ask your son!\rquote 
\par Dudley\rquote s hands jerked upwards to cover his mouth. With his parents\rquote  and Harry\rquote s eyes upon him, he slowly lowered them again and asked, \lquote There are ... more of them?\rquote 
\par \lquote More?\rquote  laughed Harry. \lquote More than the two that attacked us, you mean? Of course there are, there are hundreds, maybe thousands by this time, seeing as they feed off fear and despair \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote All right, all right,\rquote  blustered Vernon Dursley. \lquote You\rquote ve made your point \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote I hope so,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote because once I\rquote m seventeen, all of them \endash  Death Eaters, Dementors, maybe even Inferi, which means dead bodies enchanted by a Dark wizard \endash 
 will be able to find you and will certainly attack you. And if you remember the last time you tried to outrun wizards, I think you\rquote ll agree you need help.\rquote 
\par There was a brief silence in which the distant echo of Hagrid smashing down a wooden front door seemed to reverberate through the intervening years. Aunt Petunia was looking at Uncle Vernon; Dudley was staring at Harry. Finally Uncle Vernon blurted out, 
\lquote But what about my work? What about Dudley\rquote s school? I don\rquote t suppose those things matter to a bunch of layabout wizards \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Don\rquote t you understand?\rquote  shouted Harry. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote They will torture and kill you like they did my parents!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par \lquote Dad,\rquote  said Dudley in a loud voice, \lquote Dad \endash  I\rquote m going with these Order people.\rquote 
\par \lquote Dudley,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote for the first, time in your life, you\rquote re talking sense.\rquote 
\par He knew that the battle was won. If Dudley was frightened enough to accept the Order\rquote 
s help, his parents would accompany him: there could be no question of being separated from their Diddykins. Harry glanced at the carriage clock on the mantelpiece.
\par \lquote They\rquote ll be here in about five minutes,\rquote  he said, and when none of the Dursleys replied, he left the room. The prospect of parting \endash  probably forever \endash 
 from his aunt, uncle and cousin was one that he was able to contemplate quite cheerfully, but there was nevertheless a certain awkwardness in the air. What did you say to one another at the end of sixteen years\rquote  solid dislike?
\par Back in his bedroom, Harry fiddled aimlessly with his rucksack, then poked a couple of owl nuts through the bars of Hedwig\rquote s cage. They fell with dull thuds to the bottom, where she ignored them.
\par \lquote We\rquote re leaving soon, really soon,\rquote  Harry told her. \lquote And then you\rquote ll be able to fly again.\rquote 
\par The doorbell rang. Harry hesitated, then headed back out of his room and downstairs: it was too much to expect Hestia and Dedalus to cope with the Dursleys on their own.
\par \lquote Harry Potter!\rquote  squeaked an excited voice, the moment Harry had opened the door; a small man in a mauve top hat was sweeping him a deep bow. \lquote An honour, as ever!\rquote 
\par \lquote Thanks, Dedalus,\rquote  said Harry, bestowing a small and embarrassed smile upon the dark-haired Hestia. \lquote It\rquote s really good of you to do this ... they\rquote re through here, my aunt and uncle and cousin ...\rquote 
\par \lquote Good day to you, Harry Potter\rquote s relatives!\rquote  said Dedalus happily, striding into the living room. The Dursleys did not look at all happy to be addressed thus; Harry half expect
ed another change of mind. Dudley shrank nearer to his mother at the sight of the witch and wizard.
\par \lquote I see you are packed and ready. Excellent! The plan, as Harry has told you, is a simple one,\rquote  said Dedalus, pulling an immense pocket watch out of his waistcoat and examining it. \lquote 
We shall be leaving before Harry does. Due to the danger of using magic in your house \endash  Harry being still under-age, it could provide the Ministry with an excuse to arrest him \endash  we shall be driving, say ten miles or so, before Disa
pparating to the safe location we have picked out for you. You know how to drive, I take it?\rquote  he asked Uncle Vernon politely.
\par \lquote Know how to \endash ? Of course I ruddy well know how to drive!\rquote  spluttered Uncle Vernon.
\par \lquote Very clever of you, sir, very clever, I personally would be utterly bamboozled by all those buttons and knobs,\rquote 
 said Dedalus. He was clearly under the impression that he was flattering Vernon Dursley, who was visibly losing confidence in the plan with every word Dedalus spoke.
\par \lquote Can\rquote t even drive,\rquote  he muttered under his breath, his moustache rippling indignantly, but fortunately neither Dedalus nor Hestia seemed to hear him.
\par \lquote You, Harry,\rquote  Dedalus continued, \lquote will wait here for your guard. There has been a little change in the arrangements \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote What d\rquote you mean?\rquote  said Harry at once. \lquote I thought Mad-Eye was going to come and take me by Side-Along-Apparition?\rquote 
\par \lquote Can\rquote t do it,\rquote  said Hestia tersely. \lquote Mad-Eye will explain.\rquote 
\par The Dursleys, who had listened to all of this with looks of utter incomprehension on their faces, jumped as a loud voice screeched: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Hurry up!\rquote  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 Harry looked all around the room before realising that the voice had issued from Dedalus\rquote s pocket watch.
\par \lquote Quite right, we\rquote re operating to a very tight schedule,\rquote  said Dedalus, nodding at his watch and tucking it back into his waistcoat. \lquote We are attempting to time your departure from the house with your family\rquote 
s Disapparition, Harry; thus, the charm breaks at the moment you all head for safety.\rquote  He turned to the Dursleys. \lquote Well, are we all packed and ready to go?\rquote 
\par None of them answered him: Uncle Vernon was still staring, appalled, at the bulge in Dedalus\rquote s waistcoat pocket.
\par \lquote Perhaps we should Wait outside in the hall, Dedalus,\rquote  murmured Hestia: she clearly felt that it would be tactless for them to remain in the room while Harry and the Dursleys exchanged loving, possibly tearful farewells.
\par \lquote There\rquote s no need,\rquote  Harry muttered, but Uncle Vernon made any further explanation unnecessary by saying loudly, \lquote Well, this is goodbye, then, boy.\rquote 
\par He swung his right arm upwards to shake Harry\rquote s hand, but at the last moment seemed unable to face it, and merely closed his fist and began swinging it backwards and forwards like a metronome.
\par \lquote Ready, Diddy?\rquote  asked Aunt Petunia, fussily checking the clasp of her handbag so as to avoid looking at Harry altogether.
\par Dudley did not answer, but stood there with his mouth slightly ajar, reminding Harry a little of the giant, Grawp.
\par \lquote Come along, then,\rquote  said Uncle Vernon.
\par He had already reached the living-room door when Dudley mumbled, \lquote I don\rquote t understand.\rquote 
\par \lquote What don\rquote t you understand, Popkin?\rquote  asked Aunt Petunia, looking up at her son.
\par Dudley raised a large, ham-like hand to point at Harry.
\par \lquote Why isn\rquote t he coming with us?\rquote 
\par Uncle Vernon and Aunt Petunia froze where they stood, staring at Dudley as though he had just expressed a desire to become a ballerina.
\par \lquote What?\rquote  said Uncle Vernon loudly.
\par \lquote Why isn\rquote t he coming too?\rquote  asked Dudley.
\par \lquote Well, he \endash  he doesn\rquote t want to,\rquote  said Uncle Vernon, turning to glare at Harry and adding, \lquote you don\rquote t want to, do you?\rquote 
\par \lquote Not in the slightest,\rquote  said Harry.
\par \lquote There you are,\rquote  Uncle Vernon told Dudley. \lquote Now come on, we\rquote re off.\rquote 
\par He marched out of the room: they heard the front door open, but Dudley did not move and after a few faltering steps Aunt Petunia stopped too.
\par \lquote What now?\rquote  barked Uncle Vernon, reappearing in the door\-way.
\par It seemed that Dudley was struggling with concepts too difficult to put into words. After several moments of apparently painful internal struggle, he said, \lquote But where\rquote s he going to go?\rquote 
\par Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon looked at each other. It was clear that Dudley was frightening them. Hestia Jones broke the silence.
\par \lquote But ... surely you know where your nephew is going?\rquote  she asked, looking bewildered.
\par \lquote Certainly we know,\rquote  said Vernon Dursley. \lquote He\rquote s off with some of your lot, isn\rquote t he? Right, Dudley, let\rquote s get in the car, you heard the man, we\rquote re in a hurry.\rquote 
\par Again, Vernon Dursley marched as far as the front door, but Dudley did not follow.
\par \lquote Off with some of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 lot?\rquote 
\par Hestia looked outraged. Harry had met this attitude before: witches and wizards seemed stunned that his closest living relatives took so little interest in the famous Harry Potter.
\par \lquote It\rquote s fine,\rquote  Harry assured her. \lquote It doesn\rquote t matter, honestly.\rquote 
\par \lquote Doesn\rquote t matter?\rquote  repeated Hestia, her voice rising ominously. \lquote Don\rquote t these people realise what you\rquote 
ve been through? What danger you are in? The unique position you hold in the hearts of the anti-Voldemort movement?\rquote 
\par \lquote Er \endash  no, they don\rquote t,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote They think I\rquote m a waste of space, actually, but I\rquote m used to \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote I don\rquote t think you\rquote re a waste of space.\rquote 
\par If Harry had not seen Dudley\rquote s lips move, he might not have believed it. As it was, he stared at Dudley for several seconds before accep
ting that it must have been his cousin who had spoken; for one thing, Dudley had turned red. Harry was embarrassed and astonished himself.
\par \lquote Well ... er ... thanks, Dudley.\rquote 
\par Again, Dudley appeared to grapple with thoughts too unwieldy for expression before mumbling, \lquote You saved my life.\rquote 
\par \lquote Not really,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote It was your soul the Dementor would have taken ...\rquote 
\par He looked curiously at his cousin. They had had virtually no contact during this summer or last, as Harry had come back to Privet Drive so briefly
 and kept to his room so much. It now dawned on Harry, however, that the cup of cold tea on which he had trodden that morning might not have been a booby trap at all. Although rather touched, he was nevertheless quite relieved that Dudley appeared to have
 exhausted his ability to express his feelings. After opening his mouth once or twice more, Dudley subsided into scarlet-faced silence.
\par Aunt Petunia burst into tears. Hestia Jones gave her an approving look which changed to outrage as Aunt Petunia ran forwards and embraced Dudley rather than Harry.
\par \lquote S \endash  So sweet, Dudders ...\rquote  she sobbed into his massive chest, \lquote s \endash  such a lovely b \endash  boy ... s \endash  saying thank you \'85\rquote 
\par \lquote But he hasn\rquote t said thank you at all!\rquote  said Hestia indignantly. \lquote He only said he didn\rquote t think Harry was a waste of space!\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah, but coming from Dudley that\rquote s like \'93I love you\'94,\rquote  said Harry, torn between annoyance and a desire to laugh as Aunt Petunia continued to clutch at Dudley as if he had just saved Harry from a burning building.
\par \lquote Are we going or not?\rquote  roared Uncle Vernon, reappearing yet again at the living-room door. \lquote I thought we were on a tight schedule!\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes \endash  yes, we are,\rquote  said Dedalus Diggle, who had been watching these exchanges with an air of bemusement and now seemed to pull himself together. \lquote We really must be off. Harry \endash \rquote 
\par He tripped forwards and wrung Harry\rquote s hand with both of his own.
\par \lquote \endash  good luck. I hope we meet again. The hopes of the wizarding world rest upon your shoulders.\rquote 
\par \lquote Oh,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote right. Thanks.\rquote 
\par \lquote Farewell, Harry,\rquote  said Hestia, also clasping his hand. \lquote Our thoughts go with you.\rquote 
\par \lquote I hope everything\rquote s OK,\rquote  said Harry, with a glance towards Aunt Petunia and Dudley.
\par \lquote Oh, I\rquote m sure we shall end up the best of chums,\rquote  said Diggle brightly, waving his hat as he left the room. Hestia followed him.
\par Dudley gently released himself from his mother\rquote s clutches and walked towards Harry, who had to repress an urge to threaten him with magic. Then Dudley held out his large, pink hand.
\par \lquote Blimey, Dudley,\rquote  said Harry, over Aunt Petunia\rquote s renewed sobs, \lquote did the Dementors blow a different personality into you?\rquote 
\par \lquote Dunno,\rquote  muttered Dudley. \lquote See you, Harry.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah ...\rquote  said Harry, taking Dudley\rquote s hand and shaking it. \lquote Maybe. Take care, Big D.\rquote 
\par Dudley nearly smiled, then lumbered from the room. Harry heard his heavy footfalls on the gravelled drive, and then a car door slammed.
\par Aunt Petunia, whose face had been buried in her handker\-chief, looked round at the sound. She did not seem to have expected to find herself alone with Harry. Hastily stowing her wet handkerchief into her pocket she said, \lquote Well \endash  goodbye,
\rquote  and marched towards the door without looking at him.
\par \lquote Goodbye,\rquote  said Harry.
\par She stopped and looked back. For a moment Harry had the strangest feeling that she wanted to say som
ething to him: she gave him an odd, tremulous look and seemed to teeter on the edge of speech, but then, with a little jerk of her head, she bustled out of the room after her husband and son.
