\par Harry threw the Invisibility Cloak around his shoulders and pulled it up over his head, vanishing from sight. He was only just beginning to appreciate what had happened.
\par \lquote The others \endash  everyone at the wedding \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote We can\rquote t worry about that now,\rquote  whispered Hermione. \lquote It\rquote s you they\rquote re after, Harry, and we\rquote ll just put everyone in even more danger by going back.\rquote 
\par \lquote She\rquote s right,\rquote  said Ron, who seemed to know that Harry was about to argue, even if he could not see his face. \lquote Most of the Order was there, they\rquote ll look after everyone.\rquote 
\par Harry nodded, then remembered that they could not see him, and said, \lquote Yeah.\rquote  But he thought of Ginny and fear bubbled like acid in his stomach.
\par \lquote Come on, I think we ought to keep moving,\rquote  said Hermione.
\par They moved back up the side street and on to the main road again, where a group of men on the opposite side was singing and weaving across the pavement.
\par \lquote Just as a matter of interest, why Tottenham Court Road?\rquote  Ron asked Hermione.
\par \lquote I\rquote ve no idea, it just popped into my head, but I\rquote m sure we\rquote re safer out in the Muggle world, it\rquote s not where they\rquote ll expect us to be.\rquote 
\par \lquote True,\rquote  said Ron, looking around, \lquote but don\rquote t you feel a bit \endash  exposed?\rquote 
\par \lquote Where else is there?\rquote  asked Hermione, cringing as the men on the other side of the road started wolf-whistling at her. \lquote 
We can hardly book rooms at the Leaky Cauldron, can we? And Grimmauld Place is out if Snape can get in there ... I suppose we could try my parents\rquote  house, though I think there\rquote s a chance they might check there ... oh, I wish they\rquote 
d shut up!\rquote 
\par \lquote All right, darling?\rquote  the drunkest of the men on the other pavement was yelling. \lquote Fancy a drink? Ditch ginger and come and have a pint!\rquote 
\par \lquote Let\rquote s sit down somewhere,\rquote  Hermione said hastily, as Ron opened his mouth to shout back across the road. \lquote Look, this will do, in here!\rquote 
\par It was a small and shabby all-night caf\'e9. A light layer of grease lay on all the formica-topped tables, but it was at least empty. Harry slipped into a booth first and Ron sat next to him opposite Hermione, who had her back to the entrance 
and did not like it: she glanced over her shoulder so frequently she appeared to have a twitch. Harry did not like being stationary; walking had given the illusion that they had a goal. Beneath the Cloak he could feel the last vestiges of the Polyjuice Po
tion leaving him, his hands returning to their usual length and shape. He pulled his glasses out of his pocket and put them on again.
\par After a minute or two, Ron said, \lquote You know, we\rquote re not far from the Leaky Cauldron here, it\rquote s only in Charing Cross \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Ron, we can\rquote t!\rquote  said Hermione at once.
\par \lquote Not to stay there, but to find out what\rquote s going on!\rquote 
\par \lquote We know what\rquote s going on! Voldemort\rquote s taken over the Ministry, what else do we need to know?\rquote 
\par \lquote OK, OK, it was just an idea!\rquote 
\par They relapsed into a prickly silence. The gum-chewing waitress shuffled over and Hermione ordered two cappuccinos: as Harry was invisible, it would have looked odd to order him one. A pair of burly workmen entered the caf\'e9
 and squeezed into the next booth. Hermione dropped her voice to a whisper.
\par \lquote I say we find a quiet place to Disapparate and head for the countryside. Once we\rquote re there, we could send a message to the Order.\rquote 
\par \lquote Can you do that talking Patronus thing, then?\rquote  asked Ron.
\par \lquote I\rquote ve been practising and I think so,\rquote  said Hermione.
\par \lquote Well, as long as it doesn\rquote t get them into trouble, though they might\rquote ve been arrested already. God, that\rquote s revolting,\rquote 
 Ron added, after one sip of the foamy, greyish coffee. The waitress had heard; she shot Ron a nasty look as she shuffled off to take the new customers\rquote 
 orders. The larger of the two workmen, who was blond and quite huge, now that Harry came to look at him, waved her away. She stared, affronted.
\par \lquote Let\rquote s get going, then, I don\rquote t want to drink this muck,\rquote  said Ron. \lquote Hermione, have you got Muggle money to pay for this?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, I took out all my building society savings before I came to The Burrow. I\rquote ll bet all the change is at the bottom,\rquote  sighed Hermione, reaching for her beaded bag.
\par The two workmen made identical movements and Harry mir\-rored them without 
conscious thought: all three of them drew their wands. Ron, a few seconds late in realising what was going on, lunged across the table, pushing Hermione sideways on to her bench. The force of the Death Eaters\rquote 
 spells shattered the tiled wall where Ron\rquote s head had just been, as Harry, still invisible, yelled, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Stupefy!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par The great, blond Death Eater was hit in the face by a jet of red light: he slumped sideways, unconscious. His companion, unable to see who had cast the spell, fired another at Ron: shining black ropes flew from his wand-tip and bound Ron head to foot 
\endash  the waitress screamed and ran for the door \endash  Harry sent another Stunning Spell at the Death Eater with the twisted face who had tied up Ron, but the spell missed, rebounded on the window and hit 
the waitress, who collapsed in front of the door.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Expulso!\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
bellowed the Death Eater, and the table behind which Harry was standing blew up: the force of the explosion slammed him into the wall and he felt his wand leave his hand as the Cloak slipped off him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Petrificus Totalus!\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
screamed Hermione from out of sight, and the Death Eater fell forwards like a statue to land with a crunching thud on the mess of broken china, table and coffee. Hermione crawled out from underneath the bench, shaking bits of gla
ss ashtray out of her hair and trembling all over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote D \endash  Diffindo,\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
she said, pointing her wand at Ron, who roared in pain as she slashed open the knee of his jeans, leaving a deep cut. \lquote Oh, I\rquote m so sorry, Ron, my hand\rquote s shaking! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 Diffindo!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par The severed ropes fell away. Ron got to his feet, shaking his arms to regain feeling in them. Harry picked up his wand and climbed over all the debris to where the large, blond Death Eater was sprawled across the bench.
\par \lquote I should\rquote ve recognised him, he was there the night Dumbledore died,\rquote  he said. He turned over the darker Death Eater with his foot; the man\rquote s eyes moved rapidly between Harry, Ron and Hermione.
\par \lquote That\rquote s Dolohov,\rquote  said Ron. \lquote I recognise him from the old wanted posters. I think the big one\rquote s Thorfinn Rowle.\rquote 
\par \lquote Never mind what they\rquote re called!\rquote  said Hermione a little hyster\-ically. \lquote How did they find us? What are we going to do?\rquote 
\par Somehow her panic seemed to clear Harry\rquote s head.
\par \lquote Lock the door,\rquote  he told her, \lquote and Ron, turn out the lights.\rquote 
\par He looked down at the paralysed Dolohov, thinking fast as the lock clicked and Ron used the Deluminator to plunge the caf\'e9 into darkness. Harry could hear the men who had jeered at Hermione earlier, yelling at another girl in the distance.
\par \lquote What are we going to do with them?\rquote  Ron whispered to Harry through the dark; then, even more quietly, \lquote Kill them? They\rquote d kill us. They had a good go just now.\rquote 
\par Hermione shuddered and took a step backwards. Harry shook his head.
\par \lquote We just need to wipe their memories,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote It\rquote s better like that, it\rquote ll throw them off the scent. If we killed them, it\rquote d be obvious we were here.\rquote 
\par \lquote You\rquote re the boss,\rquote  said Ron, sounding profoundly relieved. \lquote But I\rquote ve never done a Memory Charm.\rquote 
\par \lquote Nor have I,\rquote  said Hermione, \lquote but I know the theory.\rquote 
\par She took a deep, calming breath, then pointed her wand at Dolohov\rquote s forehead and said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Obliviate.\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par At once, Dolohov\rquote s eyes became unfocused and dreamy.
\par \lquote Brilliant!\rquote  said Harry, clapping her on the back. \lquote Take care of the other one and the waitress while Ron and I clear up.\rquote 
\par \lquote Clear up?\rquote  said Ron, looking around at the partly destroyed caf\'e9. \lquote Why?\rquote 
\par \lquote Don\rquote t you think they might wonder what\rquote s happened if they wake up and find themselves in a place that looks like it\rquote s just been bombed?\rquote 
\par \lquote Oh right, yeah ...\rquote 
\par Ron struggled for a moment before managing to extract his wand from his pocket.
\par \lquote It\rquote s no wonder I can\rquote t get it out, Hermione, you packed my old jeans, they\rquote re tight.\rquote 
\par \lquote Oh, I\rquote m so sorry,\rquote  hissed Hermione, and as she dragged the waitress out of sight of the windows Harry heard her mutter a suggestion as to where Ron could stick his wand instead.
\par Once the caf\'e9 was restored to its previous condition, they heaved the Death Eaters back into their booth and propped them up facing each other.
\par \lquote But how did they find us?\rquote  Hermione asked, looking from one inert man to the other. \lquote How did they know where we were?\rquote 
\par She turned to Harry.
\par \lquote You \endash  you don\rquote t think you\rquote ve still got your Trace on you, do you, Harry?\rquote 
\par \lquote He can\rquote t have,\rquote  said Ron. \lquote The Trace breaks at seventeen, that\rquote s wizarding law, you can\rquote t put it on an adult.\rquote 
\par \lquote As far as you know,\rquote  said Hermione. \lquote What if the Death Eaters have found a way to put it on a seventeen-year-old?\rquote 
\par \lquote But Harry hasn\rquote t been near a Death Eater in the last twenty-four hours. Who\rquote s supposed to have put a Trace back on him?\rquote 
\par Hermione did not reply. Harry felt contaminated, tainted: was that really how the Death Eaters had found them?
\par \lquote If I can\rquote t use magic, and you can\rquote t use magic near me, without us giving away our position ...\rquote  he began.
\par \lquote We\rquote re not splitting up!\rquote  said Hermione firmly.
\par \lquote We need a safe place to hide,\rquote  said Ron. \lquote Give us time to think things through.\rquote 
\par \lquote Grimmauld Place,\rquote  said Harry.
\par The other two gaped.
\par \lquote Don\rquote t be silly, Harry, Snape can get in there!\rquote 
\par \lquote Ron\rquote s dad said they\rquote ve put up jinxes against him \endash  and even if they haven\rquote t worked,\rquote  he pressed on, as Hermione began to argue, \lquote so what? I swear, I\rquote d like nothing better than to meet Snape!\rquote 

\par \lquote But \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Hermione, where else is there? It\rquote s the best chance we\rquote ve got. Snape\rquote s only one Death Eater. If I\rquote ve still got the Trace on me, we\rquote ll have whole crowds of them on us wherever else we go.\rquote 
\par She could not argue, though she looked as if she would have liked to. While she unlocked the caf\'e9 door, Ron clicked the Deluminator to release the caf\'e9\rquote s light. Then, on Harry\rquote 
s count of three, they reversed the spells upon their three victims and before the waitress or either of the Death Eaters could do more than stir sleepily, Harry, Ron and Hermione had turned on the spot and vanished into th
e compressing darkness once more.
\par Seconds later Harry\rquote s lungs expanded gratefully and he opened his eyes: they were now standing in the middle of a familiar small and shabby square. Tall, dilapidated houses looked down on them from every side. Number twelv
e was visible to them, for they had been told of its existence by Dumbledore, its Secret Keeper, and they rushed towards it, checking every few yards that they were not being followed or observed. They raced up the stone steps and Harry tapped the front d
oor once, with his wand. They heard a series of metallic clicks and the clatter of a chain, then the door swung open with a creak and they hurried over the threshold.
\par As Harry closed the door behind them, the old-fashioned gas lamps sprang into life, casting flickering light along the length of the hallway. It looked just as Harry remembered it: eerie, cobwebbed, the outlines of the house-elf heads on the wall throw\-
ing odd shadows up the staircase. Long, dark curtains concealed the portrait of Sirius\rquote s mother. The only thing that was out of place was the troll\rquote s leg umbrella stand, which was lying on its side as if Tonks had just knocked it over again.

\par \lquote I think somebody\rquote s been in here,\rquote  Hermione whispered, pointing towards it.
\par \lquote That could\rquote ve happened as the Order left,\rquote  Ron murmured back.
\par \lquote So where are these jinxes they put up against Snape?\rquote  Harry asked.
\par \lquote Maybe they\rquote re only activated if he shows up?\rquote  suggested Ron.
\par Yet they remained close together on the doormat, backs against the door, scared to move further into the house.
\par \lquote Well, we can\rquote t stay here forever,\rquote  said Harry, and he took a step forwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Severus Snape?\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par Mad-Eye Moody\rquote s voice whispered out of the darkness, making all three of them jump back in fright. \lquote We\rquote re not Snape!\rquote  croaked Harry, before some
thing whooshed over him like cold air and his tongue curled backwards on itself, making it impossible to speak. Before he had time to feel inside his mouth, however, his tongue had unravelled again.
\par The other two seemed to have experienced the same unpleas\-ant sensation. Ron was making retching noises; Hermione stam\-mered, \lquote That m \endash  must have b \endash  been the T \endash  Tongue-Tying Curse Mad-Eye set up for Snape!\rquote 
\par Gingerly, Harry took another step forwards. Something shifted in the shadows at the end of the hall, and
 before any of them could say another word, a figure had risen up out of the carpet, tall, dust-coloured and terrible: Hermione screamed and so did Mrs Black, her curtains flying open; the grey figure was gliding towards them, faster and faster, its waist
-length hair and beard streaming behind it, its face sunken, fleshless, with empty eye sockets: horribly familiar, dreadfully altered, it raised a wasted arm, pointing at Harry.
\par \lquote No!\rquote  Harry shouted, and though he had raised his wand no spell occurred to him. \lquote No! It wasn\rquote t us! We didn\rquote t kill you \endash \rquote 
\par On the word \lquote kill\rquote  the figure exploded in a great cloud of dust: coughing, his eyes watering, Harry looked round to see Hermione crouched on the floor by the door with her arms over her head and Ron, who was shaki
ng from head to foot, patting her clumsily on the shoulder and saying, \lquote It\rquote s all r \endash  right ... it\rquote s g \endash  gone ...\rquote 
\par Dust swirled around Harry like mist, catching the blue gaslight, as Mrs Black continued to scream.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Mudbloods, filth, stains of dishonour, taint of shame on the house of my fathers \endash \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par \lquote SHUT UP!\rquote  Harry bellowed, directing his wand at her, and with a bang and a burst of red sparks the curtains swung shut again, silencing her.
\par \lquote That ... that was ...\rquote  Hermione whimpered, as Ron helped her to her feet.
\par \lquote Yeah,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote but it wasn\rquote t really him, was it? Just some\-thing to scare Snape.\rquote 
\par Had it worked, Harry wondered, or had Snape already blasted the horror-figure aside as casually as he had killed the real Dumbledore? Nerves still tingling, he led t
he other two up the hall, half expecting some new terror to reveal itself, but nothing moved except for a mouse skittering along the skirting board.
\par \lquote Before we go any further, I think we\rquote d better check,\rquote  whispered Hermione, and she raised her wand and said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Homenum revelio.\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par Nothing happened.
\par \lquote Well, you\rquote ve just had a big shock,\rquote  said Ron kindly. \lquote What was that supposed to do?\rquote 
\par \lquote It did what I meant it to do!\rquote  said Hermione rather crossly. \lquote That was a spell to reveal human presence, and there\rquote s nobody here except us!\rquote 
\par \lquote And old Dusty,\rquote  said Ron, glancing at the patch of carpet from which the corpse-figure had risen.
\par \lquote Let\rquote s go up,\rquote  said Hermione, with a frightened look at the same spot, and she led the way up the creaking stairs to the drawing room on the first floor.
\par Hermione waved her wand to ignite the old gas lamps, then, shivering slightly in the draughty room, she perched on the sofa, her arms wrapped tightly around her. Ron crossed to the window and moved the heavy velvet curtain aside an inch.
\par \lquote Can\rquote t see anyone out there,\rquote  he reported. \lquote And you\rquote d think, if Harry still had a Trace on him, they\rquote d have followed us here. I know they can\rquote t get in the house, but \endash  what\rquote s up, Harry?
\rquote 
\par Harry had given a cry of pain: his scar had burned again as something flashed across his mind like a bright light on water. He saw a large shadow and felt a fury that was not his own pound through his body, violent and brief as an electric shock.
\par \lquote What did you see?\rquote  Ron asked, advancing on Harry. \lquote Did you see him at my place?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, I just felt anger \endash  he\rquote s really angry \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote But that could be at The Burrow,\rquote  said Ron loudly. \lquote What else? Didn\rquote t you see anything? Was he cursing someone?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, I just felt anger \endash  I couldn\rquote t tell \endash \rquote 
\par Harry felt badgered, confused, and Hermione did not help as she said in a frightened voice, \lquote Your scar, again? But what\rquote s going on? I thought that connection had closed!\rquote 
\par \lquote It did, for a while,\rquote  muttered Harry; his scar was still painful, which made it hard to concentrate. \lquote I \endash  I think it\rquote s started opening again whenever he loses control, that\rquote s how it used to \endash \rquote 

\par \lquote But then, you\rquote ve got to close your mind!\rquote  said Hermione shrilly. \lquote Harry, Dumbledore didn\rquote t want you to use that connec\-tion, he wanted you to shut it down, that\rquote s why you were sup\-posed to 
use Occlumency! Otherwise Voldemort can plant false images in your mind, remember \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah, I do remember, thanks,\rquote  said Harry through gritted teeth; he did not need Hermione to tell him that Voldemort had once used this selfsame connection between them to lead him into a trap, nor that it had resulted in Sirius\rquote 
s death. He wished that he had not told them what he had seen and felt; it made Voldemort more threatening, as though he were pressing against the window of the room, and still the pain in his scar 
was building and he fought it: it was like resisting the urge to be sick.
\par He turned his back on Ron and Hermione, pretending to exam\-ine the old tapestry of the Black family tree on the wall. Then Hermione shrieked: Harry drew his wand again and spun round
 to see a silver Patronus soar through the drawing-room window and land upon the floor in front of them, where it solidified into the weasel that spoke with the voice of Ron\rquote s father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 \lquote Family safe, do not reply, we are being watched.\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 
\par The Patronus dissolved into nothingness. Ron let out a noise between a whimper and a groan and dropped on to the sofa: Hermione joined him, gripping his arm.
\par \lquote They\rquote re all right, they\rquote re all right!\rquote  she whispered, and Ron half laughed and hugged her.
\par \lquote Harry,\rquote  he said over Hermione\rquote s shoulder, \lquote I \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote It\rquote s not a problem,\rquote  said Harry, sickened by the pain in his head. \lquote It\rquote s your family, \rquote course you\rquote re worried. I\rquote d feel the same way.\rquote  He thought of Ginny. \lquote I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid9652640 feel the same way.\rquote 
\par The pain in his scar was reaching a peak, burning as it had done in the garden of The Burrow. Faintly, he heard Hermione say, \lquote I don\rquote t want to be on my own. Could we use the sleeping bags I\rquote ve brought and camp in here tonight?\rquote 

\par He heard Ron agree. He could not fight the pain much longer: he had to succumb.
\par \lquote Bathroom,\rquote  he muttered, and he left the room as fast as he could without running.
\par He barely made it: bolting the door behind him with trembling hands, he grasped his pounding head and fell to the floor, then, in an explosion of agony, he felt the rage tha
t did not belong to him possess his soul, saw a long room, lit only by firelight, and the great, blond Death Eater on the floor, screaming and writhing, and a slighter figure standing over him, wand outstretched, while Harry spoke in a high, cold, mercile
ss voice.
\par \lquote More, Rowle, or shall we end it and feed you to Nagini? Lord Voldemort is not sure that he will forgive this time ... You called me back for this, to tell me that Harry Potter has escaped again? Draco, give Rowle another taste of our displeasure 
... do it, or feel my wrath yourself!\rquote 
\par A log fell in the fire: flames reared, their light darting across a terrified, pointed white face \endash  with a sense of emerging from deep water Harry drew heaving breaths and opened his eyes.
\par He was spread-eagled on the cold black marble floor, his nose inches from one of the silver serpent tails that supported the large bathtub. He sat up. Malfoy\rquote 
s gaunt, petrified face seemed branded on the inside of his eyes. Harry felt sickened by what he had seen, by the use to which Draco was now being put by Voldemort.
\par There was a sharp rap on the door and Harry jumped as Hermione\rquote s voice rang out.
\par \lquote Harry, do you want your toothbrush? I\rquote ve got it here.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah, great, thanks,\rquote  he said, fighting to keep his voice casual as he stood up to let her in.
